</taxonomicName>
– L Jul – B g T: 
<bibRefCitation author="Forbes WTM" box="[347,480,1402,1424]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="1 - 433" refId="ref245268" refString="Forbes WTM (1954) Th e Lepidoptera of New York and neighboring states, Part III. Noctuidae. Cornell University Agricultural Experiment Station Memoirs 329: 1 - 433." type="journal article" year="1954">Forbes (1954)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Franclemont JG" box="[489,677,1402,1424]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="826 - 833" refId="ref245745" refString="Franclemont JG (1985) A new species of Parascotia with notes on the genera Mycterophora and Parascotia (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: incertae sedis). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 87: 826 - 833." type="journal article" year="1985">Franclemont (1985)</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="246.[140,1094,1366,1459]" box="[321,739,1437,1459]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
L: 
<bibRefCitation author="Bowman K" box="[347,499,1437,1459]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="121 - 165" refId="ref237866" refString="Bowman K (1951) An annotated list of the Lepidoptera of Alberta. Canadian Journal of Zoology 29: 121 - 165." type="journal article" year="1951">Bowman (1951)</bibRefCitation>
C: CNC, NFRC, UASM
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="246.[140,1108,1506,1672]" box="[140,388,1506,1530]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[140,388,1506,1530]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
60.10. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1913" box="[215,388,1506,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phytometrinae">Phytometrinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="246.[140,1108,1506,1672]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
A small group of small to medium-sized (
<quantity box="[609,738,1540,1566]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" unit="mm" value="25.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="20.0">20–30 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with relatively broad wings. Th e group is defined by a number of derived character states, mainly genitalic. The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1913" box="[301,468,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phytometrinae">Phytometrinae</taxonomicName>
have traditionally been included within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1851" box="[976,1103,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hypeninae">Hypeninae</taxonomicName>
, but the subfamily was reinstated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fibiger M &amp; Lafontaine JD" box="[546,893,1645,1672]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="7 - 690" refId="ref244973" refString="Fibiger M, Lafontaine JD (2005) A review of the higher classification of the Noctuidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to the holarctic fauna. Esperiana 11: 7 - 690." type="journal article" year="2005">Fibiger and Lafontaine (2005)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="247.[140,1107,166,264]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
In North America, the subfamily 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1913" box="[565,732,167,193]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phytometrinae">Phytometrinae</taxonomicName>
contains some 25 species in nine genera. The group is in need of revision. Th e lone AB species was treated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Forbes WTM" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 433" refId="ref245268" refString="Forbes WTM (1954) Th e Lepidoptera of New York and neighboring states, Part III. Noctuidae. Cornell University Agricultural Experiment Station Memoirs 329: 1 - 433." type="journal article" year="1954">Forbes (1954)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Covell CV Jr" box="[274,436,237,263]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" refId="ref240257" refString="Covell CV Jr (1984) A field guide to moths of eastern North America. Houghton Mifflin, Boston, MA, Peterson Field Guide Series No. 30, 496 pp." type="book" year="1984">Covell (1984)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="247.[140,1094,311,403]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
1684 R 
<taxonomicName authority="Grote, 1873 M Jun" authorityName="Grote" authorityYear="1873" box="[291,879,311,333]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Spargaloma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexpunctata">
<emphasis box="[291,503,311,333]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Spargaloma sexpunctata</emphasis>
Grote, 1873 M Jun
</taxonomicName>
– M Jul – B g T: 
<bibRefCitation author="Forbes WTM" box="[347,480,346,368]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 433" refId="ref245268" refString="Forbes WTM (1954) Th e Lepidoptera of New York and neighboring states, Part III. Noctuidae. Cornell University Agricultural Experiment Station Memoirs 329: 1 - 433." type="journal article" year="1954">Forbes (1954)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Covell CV Jr" box="[489,619,346,368]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" refId="ref240257" refString="Covell CV Jr (1984) A field guide to moths of eastern North America. Houghton Mifflin, Boston, MA, Peterson Field Guide Series No. 30, 496 pp." type="book" year="1984">Covell (1984)</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="247.[140,1094,311,403]" box="[321,739,381,403]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
L: 
<bibRefCitation author="Bowman K" box="[347,499,381,403]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="121 - 165" refId="ref237866" refString="Bowman K (1951) An annotated list of the Lepidoptera of Alberta. Canadian Journal of Zoology 29: 121 - 165." type="journal article" year="1951">Bowman (1951)</bibRefCitation>
C: CNC, NFRC, UASM
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="247.[140,1108,450,932]" box="[140,318,450,474]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[140,318,450,474]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
60.11. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[215,318,450,474]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Erebinae">Erebinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="247.[140,1108,450,932]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
Medium-sized to very large (
<quantity box="[462,605,483,510]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" unit="mm" value="105.0" valueMax="160.0" valueMin="50.0">50–160 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths, often with brightly color- ed hindwings or with eyespots on fore- and hingwings (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guenée" authorityYear="1852" box="[783,925,519,546]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Thermesiini">Thermesiini</taxonomicName>
). Th e subfamily contains many large colorful species, as well as several species that are active during the day. Larval hostplants are a diverse array of vascular plants, but tend to be specialized within groups, such as deciduous trees and shrubs for the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boisduval" authorityYear="1828" box="[784,904,624,650]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Catocalini">Catocalini</taxonomicName>
; a few (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McDunnough" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Caenurgina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Caenurgina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.) are occasional pests of forage crops.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="247" pageNumber="248" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="247.[140,1108,450,932]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[185,284,695,721]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Erebinae">Erebinae</taxonomicName>
occur worldwide but are most diverse and abundant in tropical and subtropical regions. Th ere are approximately 325 species in 65 genera in North America, of which 35 species are reported from AB. Th e group as a whole is in need of work, but revisions have been published for the tribe 
<taxonomicName authority="(Richards 1939)" baseAuthorityName="Richards" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[692,1009,800,826]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Melipotini">
Melipotini (
<bibRefCitation author="Richards AG Jr" box="[830,1001,800,826]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 100" refId="ref264004" refString="Richards AG Jr (1939) A revision of the North American species of the Phoberia - Melipotis - Drasteria group of moths (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae). Entomologica Americana 19: 1 - 100." type="journal article" year="1939">Richards 1939</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and the genera 
<taxonomicName authority="(Franclemont 1957)" baseAuthorityName="Franclemont" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[219,543,835,862]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Euclidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[219,310,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Euclidia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Franclemont JG" box="[323,535,835,862]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="5 - 15" refId="ref245532" refString="Franclemont JG (1957) The genus Euclidia, with the description of a new species (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: Catocalinae). Bulletin of the Brooklyn Entomological Society 52: 5 - 15." type="journal article" year="1957">Franclemont 1957</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Smith 1908)" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[597,807,835,862]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Zale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[597,645,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Zale</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Smith JB" box="[659,798,835,862]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="209 - 275" refId="ref267119" refString="Smith JB (1908) A revision of some species of Noctuidae heretofore referred to the genus Homoptera Boidsduval. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 35 (1645): 209 - 275." type="journal article" year="1908">Smith 1908</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrank" authorityYear="1802" box="[935,1030,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Catocala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[935,1030,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Catocala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Barnes W &amp; McDunnough JH" box="[279,673,871,897]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" refId="ref236525" refString="Barnes W, McDunnough JH (1918 a) Illustrations of the North American species of the genus Catocala. Memoirs of the American Museum of Natural History, New Series 3, 47 pp." type="book" year="1918">Barnes and McDunnough (1918a)</bibRefCitation>
; a modern revision of the genus is currently under way as an upcoming 
<emphasis box="[524,787,906,932]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Moths of North America</emphasis>
fascicle by Gall and Hawks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
